Chart 2: Company Revenue Trend
This chart tells the defining business story of the semiconductor decade. 
In 2010 Intel was king — highest revenue, unchallenged. 
By 2024 both TSMC and NVIDIA have surpassed Intel. TSMC won because every fabless company — NVIDIA, AMD, Apple, Qualcomm — needs TSMC to manufacture their chips.
NVIDIA won because it bet on GPUs for AI when nobody else did. 
Intel lost because it tried to do everything itself — design and manufacture — and fell behind on both. This 15 year trend is visible in one single chart

Chart 3 : Operating Margin Ranking 2024
Chart Type: Horizontal Bar Chart
Data Source: chip_companies_financials.csv
Companies Shown: NVIDIA, TSMC, Qualcomm, Micron, Samsung Memory, Marvell, AMD, Intel
Filter Applied: Year = 2024 | Actual data only (forecasts excluded)
What it shows:

Ranks 8 major semiconductor companies by their 2024 operating margin %
Operating margin = how much profit a company makes per $100 of revenue
NVIDIA leads at 59.5% — the highest in the industry
TSMC follows at 41.3% despite being a capital-intensive manufacturer
Qualcomm (31.1%), Micron (28.4%), Marvell (27.5%), Samsung Memory (26.8%) cluster in the 25–35% range
AMD at 23.6% — profitable but still investing heavily to compete with NVIDIA
Intel shown in red at 8.8% — significantly underperforming all peers in 2024

Colour Coding:

NVIDIA bar = dark green → signals best performer, industry winner
Intel bar = red → signals underperformance and financial stress
Traffic light colour coding used to make insights scannable without reading numbers

Why Horizontal Bar Chart:

Company names are long — horizontal layout gives each name clear readable space
Ranking story is best told top to bottom like a leaderboard
Single time period comparison (2024 only) — bar charts are ideal for categorical comparisons at one point in time
Line charts are for trends over time — bars are for ranking and comparison

Key Insight:

NVIDIA's 59.5% margin vs Intel's near-negative margin in 2024 tells the defining business story of the semiconductor industry — the fabless model (design only, outsource manufacturing) has decisively beaten the integrated model (design + manufacture) in the AI era
Marvell at 27.5% demonstrates consistent profitability despite competing against companies 5–10x its size


Chart 4 : Chip Price Trends
Chart Type: Line Chart with Dual Y Axis
Data Source: chip_prices.csv | 2014–2026
Products Shown: DRAM, NAND, HBM3, NVIDIA H100, NVIDIA B200
What it shows:

DRAM and NAND prices have stayed flat at $3–$8 for over a decade — these are commodity chips with no pricing power
NVIDIA H100 launched in 2022 and peaked at $35,640 — roughly 5,000 times more expensive than a DRAM chip
NVIDIA B200 launched in 2024 at an even higher price, while H100 prices started declining — showing a product generation handover happening in real time
HBM3 memory used inside AI GPUs rose from $200 to $800 — the only memory product that benefited from the AI boom

Key Insight:

The massive price gap between memory ($3–$8) and AI GPUs ($35,000+) directly explains why NVIDIA has 59.5% operating margins while memory companies struggle at 5–20%
Memory is a commodity — price is driven by supply and demand. NVIDIA GPUs are a platform — price is driven by the fact that no competitor can match the performance

Why this chart type:

Line chart chosen because price is something that changes continuously over time — lines show the journey and direction better than bars
Dual Y axis used because GPU prices and memory prices are on completely different scales — without it memory lines would be invisible on the chart

Chart 5 : Fab Capacity by Region
Chart Type: 100% Stacked Bar Chart

Data Source: fab_capacity.csv | Year 2024

Regions Shown: USA, Taiwan, South Korea, Japan, Europe, China, Middle East
What it shows:

Each bar represents one region and shows what percentage of its chip manufacturing capacity falls into Leading Edge (3–5nm), Advanced (7–16nm), Mature (22–28nm) or Legacy (40nm+) nodes
Taiwan is the only region with significant Leading Edge capacity — this is entirely TSMC manufacturing the world's most advanced chips at 3nm and 5nm
South Korea has a small Leading Edge segment from Samsung's advanced fabs
China is completely absent from Leading Edge — stuck at Mature and Legacy nodes due to export controls blocking access to ASML EUV machines
Japan and Europe are almost entirely Legacy (40nm+) — older generation manufacturing only
USA has zero Leading Edge capacity in 2024 but is actively building TSMC Arizona and Intel fabs through the CHIPS Act

Key Insight:

Taiwan manufactures the majority of the world's most advanced chips — making it the single most critical and vulnerable geography in global technology
If Taiwan faces any disruption — natural disaster, conflict, or political tension — the entire world's supply of advanced chips stops immediately
China being locked out of Leading Edge is a direct consequence of the export controls shown in Chart 6 — the two charts together tell one complete geopolitical story

Why this chart type:

100% stacked bar chosen to show the technology mix proportion within each region — not absolute volume
Makes it instantly clear which regions are technologically advanced vs outdated by just looking at the colour distribution


Chart 6 : Export Control Severity
Chart Type: Clustered Column Chart

Data Source: export_controls.csv | 34 actions | 2018–2026

Grouped By: US Administration (Trump 1.0, Biden, Trump 2.0)
Understanding the two bars:

Blue bar = Sum of Severity Score that year — each export control action is scored 1–10 based on how damaging it is to China's chip industry. Higher score = more impactful restriction. The blue bar adds up all scores in that year
Orange bar = Count of Control ID — simply how many separate export control actions were taken that year. Each action has a unique ID (EC001, EC002 etc.)

Severity Score scale:

1–3 = Minor restriction on a specific product
4–6 = Restricts an important technology or company
7–8 = Blocks a major company or technology category
9–10 = Sweeping restriction affecting the entire semiconductor industry

What it shows:

Trump 1.0 (2018–2020) started restrictions with 1–2 actions per year — Huawei ban in 2019 scored severity 7, targeted but not sweeping
Biden (2021–2024) escalated dramatically — 2023 has the tallest blue bar because the October 2022 BIS rules scored severity 10 (maximum) blocking ALL advanced chip exports to China in one action
Trump 2.0 (2025–2026) continued aggressively — 2025 shows 7 actions including H20 chip ban and 25–50% semiconductor tariffs

Key Insight:

Export controls escalated continuously across all three administrations — this is permanent US policy not a temporary political decision
A year can have few actions but very high severity (2022 — 1 action, severity 10) or many actions with moderate severity — both bars together tell the complete story
The direct consequence of these restrictions is visible in Chart 5 — China has zero Leading Edge fab capacity because it cannot import the ASML EUV machines needed to manufacture advanced chips
Netherlands joining the restrictions was the most damaging for China — without ASML EUV machines no country can manufacture chips below 7nm

Why this chart type:

Clustered column chosen to show two metrics simultaneously — severity (blue) and count (orange) — side by side for each year
Grouping by administration makes it immediately clear which government was toughest on chip exports
Discrete yearly events are best shown as columns not lines




